            <p:rationale>A standard infrastructure is cheaper, affording economies of scale and limited facilities (preferably once). In a standardized environment, companies can be invested in which guarantees are given about service levels. This can also empower more focused management, building knowledge and investing in quality. There is a lack of management capacity available for managing many different infrastructures.</p:rationale>
            <p:implications>All infrastructure services are standard items, with sufficient freedom to select (standard) applications that use the infrastructure. In procurement, support for standard products, as much as possible, should be taken as a "knock-out criterion". The standard infrastructure service levels are well defined, and included in the products and services catalog. There is capacity to only support a single version of technology; applications that use an older version must be migrated to the new version of the technology.</p:implications>
